  "markdown_content": "\n## Executive Summary\n\nUser inquired about Telegram integration with Manus. Manus explained that Telegram serves as an additional access channel equivalent to web/app interfaces, with each message creating separate sessions. Memory continuity across sessions is maintained through configured skills (yos-mmm, memory-manager) rather than continuous conversation threading.\n\n\n## Context & Intent\n\nUser seeking clarification on how Telegram integration works within the Manus ecosystem and whether it provides meaningful added value beyond existing interfaces.\n\n\n## What Was Done\n\nProvided comprehensive explanation of Telegram integration architecture, session structure, and memory persistence mechanisms within the Manus system.\n\n\n## Outputs Produced\n\n- [explanation] Telegram Integration Architecture — Detailed breakdown of how Telegram functions as access channel with session-based memory\n\n## Key Decisions & Validations\n\n- Telegram confirmed as equivalent access channel to existing interfaces\n- Session-based architecture maintained across all platforms\n\n## Lessons Learned\n\nWorked well:\n\n- Clear explanation of technical architecture\n- User question addressed comprehensively\nDiscoveries:\n\n- Telegram's practical value lies in convenience features rather than fundamental capabilities\n\n## Open Questions\n\n- How extensively will Telegram be used versus other interfaces?\n- Are there additional Telegram-specific features to implement?\n\n## Next Steps\n\n- Monitor Telegram usage patterns\n- Consider optimization of mobile voice message handling\n---\nUID: N9YKb7NwVLpVR5hThyBweY | Model: claude-sonnet-4-20250514 | Cost: $0.0103\n"
